7	Manchester United vs Philadelphia All Stars	74 years ago today, Manchester United came to Philadelphia.\n\nWhen they needed a place to play, the choice was obvious — Lighthouse Field, B Street & Erie Avenue, Kensington. The hub of soccer in the region, and arguably the country.\n\nMay 11, 1952. The English First Division champions, fresh off their title-winning season, arrived at Lighthouse Field. Thousands of fans packed the stands to watch captain Johnny Carey, Jack Rowley, Roger Byrne, and Frank Clempson take on a Philadelphia All-Stars side drawn from the storied Lighthouse Boys Club — five-time U.S. National Junior Champions — among them United States of America 🇺🇸 Soccer Hall of Famers and Lighthouse alumni Walter Bahr, Benny McLaughlin, and Bob Gormley. Notably, Bahr — who just two years earlier had struck the shot that Joe Gaetjens deflected into the net to give the USA a 1–0 victory over England at the 1950 World Cup. The United States, for the record, has never lost to England in a competitive match.\n\nPhiladelphia lost 4–0 that day. American soccer kept growing anyway — and arguably its strongest roots were right here in Kensington, Philadelphia.\n\nThe stands Manchester United built that day still overlook Lighthouse Field and the latest generation of boys, girls, men, and women who continue to play here — a monument to one of the many ways Lighthouse, Kensington and Philadelphia have shaped the story of soccer in America.\n\nThe Lighthouse has been part of this community since 1893 — Philadelphia's oldest non-profit, with soccer in its DNA since 1897. Seven Hall of Famers and five national championships are the tip of a blue iceberg. Underneath are countless unheralded players who learned the game, the discipline, and the moral duty to give back — coaching, refereeing, and founding clubs that spread soccer across Philadelphia, the suburbs, and beyond. 74 years after Manchester United came to town, the tradition continues on the same Kensington fields — developing young men and women to serve and give back. 💙⚽\n\n#Lighthouse1893 #PhiladelphiaSoccer #Kensington #LighthouseField #ManchesterUnited #SoccerHistory #MUFC #PhillySoccer #LighthouseBoysClub #USMNT	post	\N	https://drive.google.com/file/d/15JgtKQAgXpY7YTdjp8mauAVvGNlHP41x/preview	\N	https://footballhome.org/images/posts/man-utd-1952.jpg	\N	\N	image	f	posted	\N	2026-05-11 21:11:23.717226+00	17919903030351356	\N	2026-05-11 16:29:37.603133+00	2026-05-11 21:11:23.717226+00	\N
8	49ers	Lighthouse Boys Club won the 1967 US Youth Soccer U19 Boys National Championship. One of an incredible 5 times Lighthouse has won the most prestigious trophy in youth sports. On the 50th Anniversary of winning the National Championship, the Lighthouse 49ers(Their team name at the Lighthouse Boys Club) finally receive the James P. Maguire Trophy.	post	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	image	f	draft	\N	\N	\N	\N	2026-05-14 13:13:30.036421+00	2026-05-14 13:13:30.036421+00	""
